3, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Bernd, Otto, Armin, Hans, Gunter, Hermann, Lothar, Oskar.","German: from the medieval personal name <i>Rehm</i> (see   Remy  ).","German: from Middle High German <i>reme</i> ‘frame, loom, rack’, hence a metonymic occupational name for someone who made or used such items."],"variants":[{"name":"Rahm","meanings":["German:","topographic name from Middle High German, Middle Low German <i>rām(e)</i> ‘end, target, mark’, or a habitational name from any of several places in Westphalia and Rhineland named with this word. This surname (in any of the possible senses; see also below) is also found in France (Alsace).","from Middle High German, Middle Low German <i>rām</i> ‘soot’, possibly a metonymic occupational name for a blacksmith or charcoal burner, or a nickname for a dirty person."]},{"name":"Rohm","meanings":["German:","from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Ruom</i> (Old High German <i>hruom</i> ‘fame’), a short form of <i>Ruombald</i> and similar personal names containing this element.","(<b>Röhm</b>): variant of   Rehm  . Compare   Roehm  ."]},{"name":"Rhem","meanings":["Americanized form of German   Rehm   or its variant <b>Remm</b>. This surname is found mainly among African Americans.","History: The progenitor of many of the Rhems was Melcher Rhem (or, as spelled in the surviving documents, <i>Remm</i>) from Germany, who died in 1768 in Craven County, NC. He had three sons, all surnamed <i>Rhem</i>."]},{"name":"Remy","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French/Haitian Andre, Jean-Claude, Evens, Germaine, Gisele, Henri, Hugues, Jacques, Jean Raymond, Jean-Daniel, Josee, Laurent.","French (<b>Rémy</b>); West Indian (in Haiti, Martinique, and Guadeloupe <b>Rémy</b>); Walloon and German: from a French personal name which represents a falling together of two distinct Latin names: <i>Remigius</i> (a derivative of <i>remex</i>, genitive <i>remigis</i> ‘rower, oarsman’), and <i>Remedius</i> (from <i>remedium</i> ‘cure, remedy’). The former name was borne by a 6th-century bishop of Rheims; the latter was borne by various other Christian saints of the 8th to 10th centuries. Compare   Ramey  ,   Reamy  , and   Rhamy  .","History: The surname <i>Rémy</i> of French origin is listed in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors, once along with its altered forms <i>Ramey</i> and <i>Remey</i>, and once along with the variant <i>de Rémi</i> and altered forms <i>Reamy</i> and <i>Remey</i>. It is also listed in the similar register of the Huguenot Society of America. One of Huguenot ancestors was Jacques Rémy, born <i>c.</i> 1630 in France, who by 1672 lived in Westmoreland County, VA, where he died in 1721. Many of his descendants bear the surname   Ramey  , some also   Rhamy  . — Léopold Rémy <i>dit</i> Bellefleur from Biécourt in the Vosges married Marie-Angélique Trudel in L'Ange-Gardien, QC, in 1758."]},{"name":"Roehm","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Klaus, Eberhard, Gerhard.","German (<b>Röhm</b>): variant of   Rehm  . Compare   Rohm   2."]},{"name":"Rem","meanings":["German: perhaps an altered form of   Rehm  .","American shortened form of Polish <b>Rembowski</b>: unexplained.","Dutch: from the personal name <i>Rem</i>, a short form of   Remmert   or   Rembert  ."]},{"name":"Rehmann","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt.","North German: topographic name for someone who lived in a marshy place, from Middle Low German <i>red</i> ‘bog’ + <i>man</i> ‘man’.","North German: variant of   Rehm   2, with the addition of Middle Low German <i>man</i> ‘man’."]}]},{"name":"Anton","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Common European form of   Anthony   (see cognates list), now also used in the English-speaking world."],"variants":[{"name":"Anthony","meanings":["The usual English form of the old Roman family name <i>Antonius</i>, which is of uncertain (probably Etruscan) origin. The spelling with <i>-th-</i> (not normally reflected in the pronunciation) represents a learned but erroneous attempt to associate it with Greek <i>anthos</i> ‘flower’. In the post-classical period it was a common name, borne by various early saints, most notably a 3rd-century Egyptian hermit monk, who is regarded as the founder of Christian monasticism."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Anton Rehm was born in 1080, in Augsburg, Augsburg, Bavaria, Germany. He married Catharina in 1130, in Bavaria. They were the parents of at least 2 sons."},"et":{"1080–":"1080–Surnud","1118–Female":"1118–Surnud","1148–Male":"1148–Surnud","1150–Male":"1150–Surnud","1080–Male":"1080–Surnud","1080":"1080","about 1150":"umbes 1150","1118":"1118","1148":"1148","1150":"1150","1130 to 1148":"1130","Bavaria, Holy Roman Empire":"Königreich Bayern","Augsburg Stadt Augsburg Bayern Germany":"Augsburg, Augsburg, Bayern, Saksamaa","Germany":"Saksamaa","Augsburg, Bayern, Deutschland":"Landkreis Augsburg, Bayern, Saksamaa"},"fi":{"1080–":"1080–Kuollut","1118–Female":"1118–Kuollut","1148–Male":"1148–Kuollut","1150–Male":"1150–Kuollut","1080–Male":"1080–Kuollut","1080":"1080","about 1150":"noin 1150","1118":"1118","1148":"1148","1150":"1150","1130 to 1148":"1130","Bavaria, Holy Roman Empire":"Königreich Bayern","Augsburg Stadt Augsburg Bayern Germany":"Augsburg, Augsburg, Bayern, Saksa","Germany":"Saksa","Augsburg, Bayern, Deutschland":"Landkreis Augsburg, Bayern, Saksa"},"fr":{"1080–":"1080–Décédé","1118–Female":"1118–Décédée","1148–Male":"1148–Décédé","1150–Male":"1150–Décédé","1080–Male":"1080–Décédé","1080":"1080","about 1150":"environ 1150","1118":"1118","1148":"1148","1150":"1150","1130 to 1148":"1130","Bavaria, Holy Roman Empire":"Königreich Bayern","Augsburg Stadt Augsburg Bayern Germany":"Augsburg, Augsburg, Bayern, Allemagne","Germany":"Allemagne","Augsburg, Bayern, Deutschland":"Landkreis Augsburg, Bayern, Allemagne","lifeSummary":"Ant